JOHANNESBURG - The South African Revenue Service will officially launch tax season at its Orlando East Branch in Soweto. Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba, his deputy Sfiso Buthelezi and Sars commissioner Tom Moyane will attend the launch.Moyane said filing tax returns shows South Africans' commitment to the country.READ: #Budget2017: How much tax will you be paying now?Gigaba said paying taxes allows South Africans to hold government accountable for the state of the country. The revenue service says tax season has grown into an important partnership between government and taxpayers.Sars collected over a trillion rand in the 2016/17 fiscal year, falling short by R30-billion.The receiver of revenue's under pressure to meet its target amid shrinking economic growth.eNCA